# MGS — Mini Geometric Sensor

**Geometric stability sensor for detecting hallucinations and reasoning instability in LLM outputs**

[![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.10+-blue)](https://www.python.org/)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-green.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
[![Status: MVP](https://img.shields.io/badge/status-MVP-orange)](https://github.com/[lukin-gcst]/mgs-llm-stability-sensor)

MGS computes a **G-Index** — a stability metric based on semantic coherence in embedding space.

- **Low G** (< 0.8) → hallucinations / semantic chaos  
- **G ≈ 1** → stable, coherent reasoning  
- **High G** (> 1.5) → rigid / dogmatic structure

## Quick Start

```bash
git clone https://github.com/[твой_ник]/mgs-llm-stability-sensor.git
cd mgs-llm-stability-sensor
pip install -r requirements.txt
from mgs.sensor import MGSSensor

sensor = MGSSensor()
result = sensor.analyze("Paris is the capital of France")
print(result)
# {'g_index': 0.962, 'status': 'STABLE', ...}
Features

Real-time hallucination detection during LLM generation
Batch processing & FastAPI endpoint
Lightweight (~100 MB model)
No fine-tuning required

Benchmark (example)
Factual statements → mean G: 0.94–0.97
LLM hallucinations → mean G: 0.58–0.68
Semantic chaos → mean G: 0.42–0.55
Applications

LLM hallucination detection
Reasoning stability validation
Semantic anomaly monitoring
AI safety / alignment layer

